Data Model and Rules to Define Early





hosts, sessions, session_access, photos, payments, audit_events tables with strict ownership links (host_id, session_id).



Session policy fields: require_password, password_hash, filter_mode (fixed/preset), allowed_filters, max_shots_per_user, expires_at.



Photo metadata: object key, captured timestamp, filter used, uploader identity (or anonymous token), soft-delete status.



Enforce all read/write checks server-side (never trust client UI restrictions).

Critical Product Decisions Before Build





Define what “no second try” means technically:





hard cap per user/session,



immediate lock after capture click,



no client-side discard after upload starts.



Choose identity model for guests:





full account,



lightweight verified guest identity,



anonymous with device/session token.



Decide host gallery behavior:





instant preview vs delayed reveal,



whether guests can view only their own photos or all session photos.

Reliability and UX Risks to Address





Mobile Safari camera behavior can be inconsistent; design fallback UI for permission denial, unavailable rear camera, and failed stream start.



Add resumable upload strategy or retry policy for weak event Wi-Fi; prevent duplicate photo records.



Add anti-abuse controls: per-IP/session rate limits, upload size/type validation, and signed URL expiration.



Make session QR robust: short URL, easy rejoin path, clear “session expired/locked” screens.

Cost and Retention Strategy (small scale)





For small monthly volume, storage cost is usually minor; request/egress patterns can dominate cost.



If hosts frequently download/share galleries, prioritize low-egress provider economics; if internal/private only, S3 is fine.



Implement bucket lifecycle policy to auto-delete originals at 30 days plus DB cleanup job for metadata consistency.



Track cost metrics from day one: objects per session, avg photo size, total egress per session.

Security, Privacy, and Legal Baseline





Publish clear consent/privacy copy in guest flow (what is collected, who owns photos, 30-day deletion promise).



Add terms for hosts (they are responsible for participant consent at events).



Encrypt in transit and at rest; restrict bucket to private objects with signed access.



Plan simple data rights operations: delete session early, export session, audit access logs.

Build Sequence





Phase 1: Session/payment gating + QR entry + auth.



Phase 2: Single-shot camera UX + upload pipeline + immutable capture rules.



Phase 3: Host gallery + retention jobs + basic analytics/cost dashboard.



Phase 4: Hardening (rate limits, monitoring, failure alerts, edge-case UX).

